:"1280–1312","1299–1342":"1299–1342","1304–Male":"1304–Deceased","1306–Male":"1306–Deceased","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1304":"1304"," 1330   ":"1330","abt 1304":"about 1304","1312":"1312"," 1280  ":"1280","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","1312   ":"1312","Aldford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aldford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Weaver, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weaver, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Mondrum, Chester, Eng.":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Aldford, Cheshire, England":"Aldford, Cheshire, England","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wever","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German and Dutch: occupational name for a weaver, Middle Low German <i>wever</i>, Middle Dutch <i>wever(e)</i>. Compare   Weber  .","English: variant of   Weaver  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Weber","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a weaver, Middle High German <i>wëber</i>, German <i>Weber</i>, an agent derivative of <i>weben</i> ‘to weave’. This form of the surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, and the Netherlands. In Hungary it is mostly spelled <b>Wéber</b> and <b>Véber</b>. In Russia, Slovenia, Czechia, Slovakia, and Croatia it is (also) established in the Slavicized form   Veber  , which is in Czechia also spelled <b>Vebr</b>. Compare   Waber  ,   Weaber  ,   Weaver  ,   Webber  , and   Webre  .","History: As a name of ultimately Swiss German origin the surname <i>Weber</i> is also established among the American Mennonites. However, descendants of the early Mennonite settlers, who came to PA in the early 18th century, mostly bear the Americanized form of the name (see   Weaver  )."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel Mabel de Wever was born in 1280, in Aldford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Henry de Weaver in 1299, in Aldford, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1330, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{" 1280  – 1330   ":"1280–1330","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1299–1342":"1299–1342","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1304":"1304"," 1330   ":"1330","abt 1304":"umbes 1304","1312":"1312"," 1280  ":"1280","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","1312   ":"1312","Aldford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aldford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Weaver, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weaver, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caernar